y to the conventional view that Confucian rule aims to instill virtue in all members of society, El Amine demonstrates that its main aim is to promote political order.El Amine analyzes key aspects of the Confucian political vision, including the relationship between the ruler and the people, the typology of rulers, and the role of ministers and government officials. She also looks at Confucianism's account of the mechanisms through which society is to be regulated, from welfare policies to rituals. She explains that the Confucian conception of the political leaves space open for the rule of those who are not virtuous if these rulers establish and maintain political order. She also contends that Confucians defend the duty to take part in government based on the benefits that such participation can bring to society.Classical Confucian Political Thought brings a new understanding to Confucian political theory by illustrating that it is not chiefly idealistic and centered on virtue, but rather realistic and driven by political concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConfucian ethics. 0aConfucianism and state. 0aPhilosophy, Confucian. 0aPolitical ethics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAnalects.  aChinese communists.  aChinese intellectual tradition.  aClassical Confucianism.  aConfucian ethics.  aConfucian government.  aConfucian political thought.  aConfucian politics.  aConfucianism.  aConfucians.  aHeaven.  aMencius.  aRobert Eno.  aXunzi.  acommon people.  aearly Confucians.  aeconomic measures.  ahegemons.  aheirarchical leanings.  ahuman nature.  akings.  alabor division.  ameritorious ministers.  ametaphysics.  aministers.  amodern politics.  amoral development.  amoral philosophy.  aorder.  aorderly society.  apatriarchy.  apenal force. 